<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="56" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,519,786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,519,545]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
(Modified from 
<bibRefCitation author="Lowry" box="[482,765,520,546]" pageId="1" pageNumber="65" refString="Lowry, J. K. &amp; Berents, P. B. (1996) The Erichtonius Group, a New perspective on a old problem (Cruatcea: Amphipoda: Corophioidea). Records of Australian Museum, 48, 75 - 109." type="journal article" year="1996">
Lowry &amp; Berents, 
<number box="[705,765,520,546]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) Rostrum acute. Antenna 
<number box="[1077,1092,520,546]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.0">1</number>
, peduncle article 
<number box="[1302,1317,520,546]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.0">1</number>
rectangular, not produced anterodistally or medially, without accessory flagellum. Gnathopod 
<number box="[1186,1201,560,586]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2.0">2</number>
of male adult, carpochelate, subchelate in female. Pereopods 
<number box="[662,729,600,626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="5.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="3.0">3 to 7</number>
with dactyli directed posteriorly. Pereopod 
<number box="[1241,1256,600,626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="5.0">5</number>
coxa in female larger than in male, without fringe of long setae; dactylus with large unguis and 
<number box="[1108,1152,640,666]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
small accessory spines. Dactyli of pereopods 
<number box="[409,424,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="6.0">6</number>
and 
<number box="[485,500,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="7.0">7</number>
with 
<number box="[570,614,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
small accessory spines. Pereopod 
<number box="[1028,1042,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="7.0">7</number>
elongate, Pleopods 
<number box="[1285,1300,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number box="[1360,1375,680,706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="3.0">3</number>
with inner rami reduced, 
<number box="[402,411,720,746]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.0">1</number>
-articulate. Uropod 
<number box="[658,673,720,746]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2.0">2</number>
with 
<number box="[750,765,720,746]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.0">1</number>
ramus. Uropod 
<number box="[971,986,720,746]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="3.0">3</number>
unirramous, ramus vestigial bearing recurved spines.
</paragraph>
